Here's the severity-ranked audit:

---

## CRITICAL

### 1. Missing Assertion — `GetUser_NonExistentId_ReturnsNull` (line 20–25)
No assertion at all. The test always passes regardless of what `GetById` returns.
```csharp
// Fix: replace the comment with
Assert.IsNull(user);
```

### 2. Swallowed Exception — `AddUser_DuplicateId_ThrowsException` (line 28–41)
The `try/catch` silently passes even if *no* exception is thrown (execution falls off the end of the method). This is the classic "swallowed exception" pattern.
```csharp
// Fix: replace entire body with
Assert.ThrowsException<InvalidOperationException>(() => repo.Add(new User(1, "Bob")));
```

### 3. Self-Comparing Assertion — `DeleteUser_RemovesFromRepository` (line 49)
`Assert.AreEqual(repo.Count, repo.Count)` compares the value to itself — it can never fail. The delete is never verified.
```csharp
// Fix:
Assert.AreEqual(0, repo.Count);
// or additionally:
Assert.IsNull(repo.GetById(1));
```

---

## WARNING

### 4. Broad Exception Type — `AddUser_NullUser_ThrowsArgumentNullException` (line 80)
Method name says `ThrowsArgumentNullException` but it asserts on the base `Exception` type. Any exception (e.g. `NullReferenceException` from a missing null-check) would pass.
```csharp
// Fix:
Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(() => repo.Add(null!));
```

### 5. Weak Negative Assertion — `UpdateUser_ChangesName` (line 59)
`Assert.IsTrue(user.Name != "Alice")` only asserts the name *changed from the old value* — it doesn't verify it changed *to the correct value*. A bug that sets the name to `""` would pass.
```csharp
// Fix:
Assert.AreEqual("Alicia", user.Name);
```

### 6. Incomplete Assertion — `GetUser_ExistingId_ReturnsUser` (line 11–17)
`Assert.IsNotNull(user)` proves a user was returned but never checks it's the *right* user. A bug returning a wrong user would pass.
```csharp
// Fix: add
Assert.AreEqual(1, user.Id);
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", user.Name);
```

---

## INFO

### 7. Unused Field — `_client` (line 8)
A `static readonly HttpClient` is declared but never used in any test. This is dead code that suggests a copy-paste artifact or an incomplete test, and it introduces an unnecessary network dependency type.
```csharp
// Fix: delete the field entirely.
```

### 8. Console.WriteLine Instead of Assertion — `SearchUsers_ByPartialName_FindsMatches` (line 92)
The `Console.WriteLine` on line 92 adds no verification value. While the test itself has a valid assertion on line 91, the log line can give a false sense of thoroughness. Consider also asserting the *contents* of the results.
```csharp
// Fix: remove the Console.WriteLine; optionally add:
Assert.IsTrue(results.Any(u => u.Name == "Alice"));
Assert.IsTrue(results.Any(u => u.Name == "Alicia"));
```

---

**Summary:** 3 Critical findings (tests that _cannot_ catch bugs), 3 Warnings (tests that catch some bugs but miss important ones), and 2 Info-level issues. The Critical items (#1–#3) are the most likely root causes of the prod incident — they give a green test suite while exercising no meaningful verification.
